Ok, say you have a favorite skintone but you can't find it in one of the various bodyshape combo meshes that I will be sharing. Well, here's a very simple lil' tute that will walk you step by step through the process of converting your skintone into a different shape...

What you need:
- Bodyshop
- Photoshop, or your favorite photo editing program
- and a few minutes!

To start:
- Start up Bodyshop
- Wait...
- And wait...
- And wait some more! (however long it might take your Bodyshop to boot up! )

Okay! FINALLY!
- Start a new project...
- Create Genetics...
- Skin Tone...
- Choose your favorite skin...




- And export it...
- Give it a name, any name really, it doesn't matter as long as you can find it in your 'Projects' folder.




- Open your 'Projects' folder. Found MyDocuments -> EA Games -> The Sims 2 -> Projects -> "Whatever you named it"
- You will find roughly 40+ .png/.bmp files (for some reason, mine show as .bmp files, but I think they are normally .png files! ) and 1 .package file
- DON'T TOUCH/MESS with the .package file or the swatch.png/.bmp!
- Alter as desired




- Now go back to BS and close out of this project and start a new skin project



- this time choose one of my skin combos that you want to use




- name it something that you will remember ( I usually name mine something like = "skin-SBB&RIO" that way I know what it is and know the size!)




- Open another project folder (follow the above path to this new project folder) you should now have 2 folders open on your desktop = 1 for the desired skin color and the other for the desired skin size!
- Go to the 1st folder and highlight then copy the 1st 29ish .png/.bmp's before the swatch.png/.bmp





continued next post...

cont...

- Then go to the 2nd folder (the desired size folder) and paste
- Click "Yes" when asked if you want to overwrite



- Go back to folder 1 and highlight the remaining 10ish .png's, copy and paste again and "Yes" to overwrite. You do not need to copy/paste the various hair files, just the skintoned ones. There are files marked hair, you DO need these! As long as they are the skintones! See next pic...



- Now, if you so choose, you can open your swatch.png in your photo-editing program and give it a custom look/picture so that it is easier to identify it in Bodyshop.
- If there are any other remaining edits that you want to do to your new skin, now is the time to open the .png in your photo-editing program. You can save it in your photo-editing program and go into BS and hit the refresh button (the little circular arrow) in the bottom left corner to see what your edits did to the skin.




- Give your skin a "tag line", something like "SBB&RIO-Pona-Tan_editedbyG-Knee" or whatever.
- Then, if you're happy with your skin, hit the "Import" button at the bottom of the Project Panel and your files will be imported into the game for you.
- And just like that, you have a new skin the color of your choosing with the custom bodyshapes that you asked for!

I hope this is helpful for ya'll!!!

ENJOY!

What a great tutorial! We won't discuss how stupidly I did this my first ten times.

As for that swatch file, I like to slap a picture on it, and briefly describe the skin files, otherwise there's a bunch of those swatches in your skin inventory, making skin selection unnecessarily tedious.

All you have to do, using your photo image program (such as Gimp or Photoshop), go into Documents>EA Games> The Sims 2>Projects>"whatever file you named that new skin" folder.

1. Find the swatch.bmp, and open it with your program
2. Open whatever image you want posted on that swatch,
3. Paste that image onto the swatch.bmp file (Select all>copy>paste)
4. Type a description to fit on that tiny space (Usually you have to use a really small sized font)
5. "Flatten" the layer(s)
6. Save it
7. Import it back to the game while in bodyshop

If you don't like what anything looks like, you can redo it.
